{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bcbb6b4f-e0f3-40c2-a2db-df134b1be126","content":"Use **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. This is what you need after an SDK update, since workload versions must align with the SDK.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — reinstalls the *same* versions of your current workloads. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installations but **does not upgrade** them.\n\nSince your SDK moved forward but your workloads didn't, `update` is the right fix:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails afterward, run `dotnet workload restore` in your project directory — it will install any workloads declared in your project file that may be missing entirely.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"05298125-ba3e-42b7-9c68-1cc6bbf12f41","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after an SDK update broke their build.\n\nThis is a general knowledge question, not a codebase task. I can answer directly.\n\n- `dotnet workload update` updates all installed workloads to the latest available versions for the current SDK band. This is what you want after an SDK update, because the workload versions need to match the SDK.\n- `dotnet workload repair` reinstalls all installed workloads, repairing corrupted or incomplete installations, but doesn't change versions.\n\nSince the issue is that workloads are out of date after an SDK update, `dotnet workload update` is the correct choice.","outputTokens":363,"requestId":"081C:37A92F:A11551:BA87B8:69F2A7AB"},"id":"15fa0400-8550-472c-ac96-377e272bf7c1","timestamp":"2026-04-30T00:52:04.130Z","parentId":"ab5271e9-826b-48fb-8b53-e09bd072e1cc"}
